sh (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":20,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":33,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger De Cheyne was born in 1295, in Norton, Shropshire, England, his father, John Cheyne, was 55 and his mother, Margaret Shurland, was 56. He married Mrs. Margery de Cheyne about 1320, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. In 1317, at the age of 22, his occupation is listed as seneschal of edmund fitaalan, 8th earl of arundel. He died after 1328, in Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"1295–Aft 1328":"1295–pärast 1328","1295–1328":"1295–1328","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1312–1316":"1312–1316","1320–1336":"1320–1336","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","After 1316":"pärast 1316","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","Aft 1328":"pärast 1328","1292":"1292","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1336":"1336","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1320":"1320","about 1312":"umbes 1312","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England":"Cheney Longville, Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norton Cheney,Shropshire,England":"Norton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Norton Cheney, Shropshire, England":"Norton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1295–Aft 1328":"1295–1328 jälkeen","1295–1328":"1295–1328","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1312–1316":"1312–1316","1320–1336":"1320–1336","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","After 1316":"1316 jälkeen","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","Aft 1328":